-- Hong Kong Stocks Decline on Technology Shares Before PMI
-- B y   K a n a   N i s h i z a w a
-- 2013-11-05T01:39:46Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-11-05/hong-kong-stocks-decline-on-technology-shares-before-pmi.html
Hong Kong  stocks  fell a second day as
information technology shares declined ahead of a private report
on  China ’s services industries.  The  Hang Seng Index (HSI)  fell 0.9 percent to 22,990.96 as of
9:37 a.m. in Hong Kong after rising as much as 0.5 percent. The
Hang Seng China Enterprises Index of mainland shares listed in
the city lost 1 percent to 10,572.08.  The Hang Seng Index jumped 17 percent from this year’s low
on June 24 through yesterday on signs China’s economy is
stabilizing. Hong Kong’s benchmark index  traded  at 11.1 times
estimated earnings yesterday, compared with 16 for the Standard
& Poor’s 500 Index.  HSBC Holdings Plc and Markit Economics Ltd. are due to
release a China services Purchasing Managers’ Index for October
today after a non-manufacturing gauge compiled by the government
rose to the highest level this year. The increase follows
better-than-estimated readings for two indexes of factory
activity last week.  Futures on the S&P 500 lost 0.1 percent today. The U.S.
equity gauge gained 0.4 percent yesterday as Exxon Mobil Corp.
and U.S. Steel Corp. led a rally in commodity stocks. Investors
are awaiting data on employment and economic growth to gauge the
health of the U.S. economy after the Federal Reserve last week
said it needs to see more evidence of sustained improvement
before reducing the pace of its monthly bond purchases.  HSBC gained 1.4 percent to HK$86.30 to lead gains after
saying third-quarter pretax profit jumped 30 percent to $4.53
billion from a year earlier, boosted by earnings in Hong Kong
and cost cuts. The bank also said it’s among financial companies
being probed by regulators over foreign-exchange trades.  Hong Kong Exchanges & Clearing Ltd. yesterday said it plans
to offer after-hours trading on more futures contracts. The
bourse is also considering extending such trading to around
midnight from 11 p.m.  To contact the reporter on this story:
